### 2. [error-handling] pds-core/index.ts line 198-208: All createAccount failures treated as handle collision

**Original comment:**
> This catch also hides invite-code misconfiguration, datastore failures, and provider errors as a collision.

Currently:
```ts
} catch (createErr: unknown) {
  logger.warn({ err: createErr, handle: chosenHandle }, "chosen handle collision at createAccount")
  res.redirect(303, `https://${authHostname}/auth/choose-handle?error=handle_taken`)
  return
}
```

**Fix:** Use a pre-check pattern instead of trying to inspect the error class. `UserAlreadyExistsError` is not exported from `@atproto/pds` so instanceof checks are fragile. Instead:

1. Before calling `createAccount`, check if the handle already exists:
```ts
const existingHandle = await pds.ctx.accountManager.getAccount(chosenHandle)
if (existingHandle) {
  logger.warn({ handle: chosenHandle }, "chosen handle already taken (pre-check)")
  res.redirect(303, `https://${authHostname}/auth/choose-handle?error=handle_taken`)
  return
}
```

2. Then call `createAccount` — if it throws, it is NOT a handle collision (we just checked), so log as error and return 500:
```ts
try {
  account = await provider.accountManager.createAccount(...)
  did = account.sub
} catch (createErr: unknown) {
  logger.error({ err: createErr, handle: chosenHandle }, "createAccount failed (not a handle collision)")
  res.status(500).type("html").send(renderError("Account creation failed. Please try again."))
  return
}
```

Note: there is a tiny TOCTOU race between the pre-check and createAccount. In the unlikely event of a race collision, the user gets a generic 500 instead of "handle taken" — acceptable since the race window is milliseconds and the user can retry.

**Context:** `pds.ctx.accountManager.getAccount(handle)` is already used in the `/_internal/check-handle` endpoint in the same file, so this pattern is consistent.

