Review of ePDS-ipm found: the .otp-input CSS class has 'letter-spacing: 8px' hardcoded in all three route files. This value was presumably tuned for 8-digit codes. It is not adjusted when OTP_LENGTH changes.

Affected files (all three have identical CSS):
- login-page.ts line 273: .otp-input { ... letter-spacing: 8px; ... }
- recovery.ts line 297 (in CSS const): .otp-input { ... letter-spacing: 8px; ... }
- account-login.ts line 220 (in CSS const): .otp-input { ... letter-spacing: 8px; ... }

Impact: For shorter codes (OTP_LENGTH=4 or 5), the 8px letter-spacing causes the digits to spread very wide in the fixed-width input box, potentially overflowing or looking awkward. For longer codes (10-12 digits), the spacing may be too tight relative to the font size.

The letter-spacing is a cosmetic issue and does not break functionality, but it degrades UX for non-default OTP lengths.

Suggested fix: either make letter-spacing dynamic (injected via inline style using opts.otpLength) or use a more conservative value like 4-6px that works acceptably across the 4-12 digit range.

Review of ePDS-ipm found: all four subtitle locations use the article "a" unconditionally before the digit count. For OTP_LENGTH=8 (the default) and OTP_LENGTH=11, this renders as "We sent a 8-digit code" and "We sent a 11-digit code" — both grammatically incorrect. English requires "an" before numbers whose spoken form starts with a vowel sound: 8 ("eight"), 11 ("eleven").

Affected locations:
1. login-page.ts line 368: 'We sent a ' + otpLength + '-digit code to ' + masked
2. login-page.ts line 500: same string (duplicate in the auto-send callback)
3. recovery.ts line 254: 'we sent a ${opts.otpLength}-digit code to'
4. account-login.ts line 188: 'We sent a ${opts.otpLength}-digit code to'

The bug was introduced by the spec itself (ePDS-ipm.3 and ePDS-ipm.4 both specify 'a ' + otpLength), so the worker followed the spec correctly but the spec was wrong.

Fix: use a helper to pick the right article:
  const article = [8, 11].includes(otpLength) ? 'an' : 'a';
  // or more robustly: /^[aeiou]/i.test(otpLength.toString()) ? 'an' : 'a'
  // Note: 8 -> 'eight' starts with vowel; 11 -> 'eleven' starts with vowel
  // All others in range 4-12 start with consonants.

